@node "Introduction" Introduction

                             @{b}Introduction@{ub}


MaxRexx is actually similar to the Assembler, C, E and AMOS Doorpacks in that it
provides you with a way of writing doors for Maxs BBS. MAXREXX allows you to
write doors for Maxs BBS in AREXX, which is as far as I know the first of its
kind for Maxs BBS. A lot of people do program in AREXX and nothing else, and AMOS
doors aren't exactly system friendly. MaxRexx may even be a benefit to those who
can already program in the more complex languages such as Asm, C and E for its
simplicity, you can literally knock up doors in seconds. It provides some other
functions that you can't implement in doors in other languages with ease, for
example you can execute a MAXREXX door from within another MAXREXX door. You can
control other system programs that have AREXX ports, from within a MAXREXX door.
It also makes it very easy to have doors communicating with each other over a
multiline system making internode chat doors easy.

@endnode
@node "Requirements" Requirements


                             @{b}Requirements@{ub}


- Maxs BBS (Only tested with 1.54 but should work with earlier versions)
- Should also work with Maxs Pro.
- Tested and works with Zeus (Paragon functions only!)

- REXXMAST running (As supplied with OS 2 and above)
  It is recommended that you have this running everytime you start workbench so
  ideally it should be placed in WBStartup.

- RX in the command path (As supplied with OS 2 and above)
  The default is for it to be located in the command path by a standard
  workbench install.

- T: must be assigned somewhere.
  Usually RAM:T/ by a standard workbench install.

- A little knowledge of AREXX is useful however it shouldn't be too hard for
  those who have never used AREXX to learn how the doors are created.
  See examples included in distribution.

- Recommended OS version 3.0+
  Should work on OS 2.04+ however this is as yet, untested.

@endnode

@node "Installation & Usage" Installation & Usage



                         @{b}Installation & Usage@{ub}


MaxRexx should be run as the door from maxs with function 34, with it's path
entered in the string box and the path of the script following, as an example:-

Key:  Function:  Extra:  Lo acc:  Hi Acc:  Filename/Name/Dest/Path:
A     34         0       10       10000    BBS:maxrexx Doors:test.rexx


So when a user runs the door, in this case by pressing 'A', MaxRexx
automatically executes the script test.rexx .

Please make sure you have read the @{"Requirements" link "Requirements"0}.

@endnode

@node "Commands" Commands



                               @{b}Commands@{ub}

Please note that all commands are @{b}CASE SENSITIVE@{ub} and require the dollar
sign ($) to preceed them.

The AREXX port of MAXREXX is MAXSERVEx, where x is the number of the node.
Please see example scripts on how to open the MAXREXX port correctly.

Apostrophes must be used, where shown in the Synopsis.

@{b}@{u}Commands Added At Version 0.9b@{uu}@{ub}

Please remember that all commands will return rc as being zero if the commands
was @{b}successful@{ub} and return -1 if the command @{b}failed.@{ub}

Command:  @{b}$BCOLOUR@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$BCOLOUR x@{ub}
Function: Changes the colour of the background depending on the value x. See
          $FCOLOUR for colour details.

Command:  @{b}$CHECKFILE@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$CHECKFILE 'filename' @{ub}
Function: Checks to see whether the file exists in the internal Maxs File Base
          only. Please note, apostrophes must be included.

Results:  If rc=-1 then the file @{b}is not@{ub} in the internal maxs file base
          If rc=0 then the file @{b}is@{ub} in the maxs file base

Command:  @{b}$CLS@{ub}
Function: Clears the screen and returns the cursor to ANSI 0,0 the top left hand
          corner of the screen.

Command:  @{b}$END@{ub}
Function: Closes the door down returning control the BBS. This command should
          not be issued after $TWIT has been called.

Command:  @{b}$FCOLOUR@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$FCOLOUR x@{ub}
Function: Changes the foreground colour depending on the value of x

          0    BLACK
          1    RED
          2    GREEN
          3    YELLOW/BROWN
          4    BLUE
          5    PINK/MAGENTA
          6    CYAN/LIGHT BLUE
          7    WHITE

Command:  @{b}$HOTKEY@{ub}
Function: Makes the door wait until the user has pressed a key.
Results:  The ASCII value of that key is returned!
          NB @{b}Not the actual key letter itself@{ub}

Command:  @{b}$INPUT@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$INPUT X@{ub}
Function: Waits for the user of the door to input some text, giving them X
          number of spaces in which to enter it. X is an integer.
Results:  If rc=-1 then a string of zero length was entered.
          IF rc>-1 then it returns the string that the user entered.

Command:  @{b}$MENUFUNC@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$MENUFUNC 'function,extra,string'@{ub}
Function: Runs a maxs internal menu function. Please see the Maxs BBS manual
          for a list of functions. If NIL is given as the string then no
          string will be passed to the function.

Command:  @{b}$NEWLINE@{ub}
Function: Forces the cursor to move onto the start of the next line

Command:  @{b}$PAGEFLAG@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$PAGEFLAG x@{ub}
Function: Sets the maxs internal page flag depending on the value of x.
          1    Set The Flag
          0    Remove the Flag

Command:  @{b}$PRINT@{ub}
Synopsis  @{b}$PRINT string@{ub}
Function: Prints text to the screen without moving the cursor to a newline

Command:  @{b}$PRINTLN@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$PRINTLN 'string'@{ub}
Function: Prints text to the screen with a carriage return at the end to force
          the cursor onto a newline. The string should be enclosed in
          apostrophes.

Command:  @{b}$SHOWANSI@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$SHOWANSI 'filename'@{ub}
Function: Displays a textfile or an ANSI file onto the maxs screen. 

Command:  @{b}$TWIT@{ub}
Function: Kicks the current user off the BBS and hangs up. $TWIT automatically
          issues the $END command itself, so you do not need to add $END
          yorself after issuing $TWIT.

Command:  @{b}$USERSTR@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$USERSTR infonum@{ub}
Function: Returns some string information about the user currently using the
          door. infonum is an integer and the following values return assocated
          information.

          1    Name
          2    Password
          3    Suburb
          100  Phone Number
          101  Computer
          102  Comment
          7    Door Path
          8    BBS Path
          9    Date
          10   Time

          This is by no means a complete list.

Command:  @{b}$USERVAL@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$USERVAL infonum@{ub}
Function: Returns some information in the form of a string depending on the
          value of infonum. For example, if infonum =1 then it will return the
          access level of the user currently using the door. A detailed list
          will be given in future documents.


@{b}@{u}Commands Added At Version 1.0a@{uu}@{ub}

Command:  @{b}$CLOSEWINDOW@{ub}
Function: Closes any windows which you may have open on the Maxs Screen. You
          must do this @{b}BEFORE@{ub} your AREXX program ends. MaxRexx has been
          programmed so that if you issue this command twice, it should not
          crash.
Results:  If rc=0 then the window closed fine
          If rc=-1 then the window failed to close, or there was no window open
          to close.

Command:  @{b}$MAXBEEP@{ub}
Function: Beeps the maxs screen.

Command:  @{b}$NEWUSERINT@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$NEWUSERINT 'int,value'@{ub}
Function: Changes integer data about the user, for example their access level or
          the amount of time they have left. The apostrophes must be included in
          the command.

Command:  @{b}$NOWAITHOTKEY@{ub}
Function: Receives a key press from the user, however it doesn't not wait for a
          keypress then report the key, the key must be pressed the same time as
          the function is called.
Results:  Returns the ASCII value of the key pressed as a string. See @{b}$HOTKEY
          @{ub}for more details.

Command:  @{b}$OPENWINDOW@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$OPENWINDOW 'width,height,title'@{ub}
Function: Opens a window on the first maxs screen only. Width and height are
          both integers which governs the size of the window. Title is a
          string which is displayed on the title bar. @{b}This command is OS
          illegal because the Maxs Screen is not a public screen, and therefore
          does not check for visitor windows. Use this command with care and
          thought. If Maxs tries to quit, or iconify then it will crash if there
          is a window open on the screen.@{ub} Although this command is OS
          illegal it will not crash or make your system unstable by using it,
          as long as you take into account the above precaution.

Results:  If rc=0 then the window opened successfully.
          If rc=1 then the window failed to open, likely causes are the window
          dimensions exceeding the size of the maxs screen or the Maxs Screen
          being iconified at the time of attempting to open the window.

Command:  @{b}$WINCOL@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$WINCOL x@{ub}
Function: Changes the colour of the text to be printed on the window that you've
          opened, to the value x. The colour that x represents depends on the
          palette you are using. x is an integer. It should be safe to issue
          this command even when there is no window open, however good
          programming practice dictates that you make sure your code opens a
          window first.

Command:  @{b}$WINTEXT@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$WINTEXT 'x,y,string'@{ub}
Function: Prints the text string on the currently opened window on the maxs
          screen. It prints at position x,y which are both integers. x,y refer
          to the number of pixels and not the number of characters like ANSI
          does. x and y are both integers. It should be safe to issue this command,
          even if there is no window open, however good programming practice
          dictates that you should make sure your code opens a window first.

@{b}@{u}Commands Added At Version 1.1@{uu}@{ub}

Command:  @{b}$CENTRE@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$CENTRE 'y,string'@{ub}
Function: It prints a piece of text which is centred on the screen at line y.
          If the string is longer than 80 characters it will be truncated as 80
          characters is the maximum one line can hold.

Command:  @{b}$GOTO@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$GOTO 'x,y'@{ub}
Function: It moves the ANSI cursor to the location x,y. 

Command:  @{b}$NODEOPEN@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$NODEOPEN@{ub}
Function: It returns the number of the node that is open. For example 
          0 = Local Login
          1 = Line 1
          2 = Line 2  etc...
Results:  RC = Node number currently open.

@{b}@{u}Commands Added At Version 1.2@{uu}@{ub}

Command:  @{b}$ANSIBOX@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$ANSIBOX 'x,y'@{ub}
Function: Draws a box in ANSI characters from the current cursor position. x and
          y are both integers. x is the width of the box and y is the height.
          Minimum value of x and y is 2. Please note, if your box doesn't fit
          on the screen it will be warped.

Command:  @{b}$ASCIIBOX@{ub}
Synopsis: @{b}$ASCIIBOX 'x,y'@{ub}
Function: Draws a box in ASCII characters from the current cursor position. x
          and y are both integers. x is the width of the box and y is the
          height. Minimum value of x is 3, minimum value of y is 2. Please note
          , if your box doesn't fit on the screen it will be warped.

@endnode

