                       @{u}@{b}Example Scripts@{ub}@{uu}

For more details, see the comment at the start of the scripts.

@{b}@{u}Everything.rexx@{uu}@{ub}

Script which tests most of the functions available in MaxRexx.


@{b}@{u}Doorstarter.rexx@{uu}@{ub}

Conversion of the simple example door that is distributed with the Maxs ASM door
pack.

@{b}@{u}ExampleDoor.rexx@{uu}@{ub}

Simple script that gives a basic example of how to set up a MaxRexx door.

@{b}@{u}Piggy.rexx@{uu}@{ub}

A door written for MaxRexx by Kevin Sherman which is a dice game called Piggy.

@{b}@{u}Quit.rexx@{uu}@{ub}

A script which can be used to terminate MaxRexx from the CLI.

@{b}@{u}WindowExample.rexx@{uu}@{ub}

Example script that shows you how to open a window on the Maxs screen.

@{b}@{u}Mainscript.rexx & subscript.rexx@{uu}@{ub}

Example scripts to show you how to execute a MaxRexx door from within
another MaxRexx door.
@endnode

@node "Tips" Tips

                    @{u}@{b}Tips & Troubleshooting@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}Q. Sometimes MaxRexx hangs and I can't quit it. What is the problem?@{ub}

A. MaxRexx hasn't actually hung, what it's doing is waiting to receive an
AREXX command from the Arexx Script you are trying to run with it. The
problem is a parsing error in the script which has been picked up by RX.
Check the last entry in T:MaxRexx.errors which will point you in the right
direction. Common problems are, missing quote marks, quote marks in the
wrong position, or commands mispelled. Use quit.rexx to quit MaxRexx when
this occurs. See script for usage.

@{b}Q. I've written a script which I want to use on my multiline BBS, how do
I test to make sure it works?@{ub}

A. There is a package called NullModem.device which lets you use a terminal
program to call your own BBS on the same machine. It works by fooling the
terminal program into thinking it's got a modem and fools Maxs into thinking
it has just connected to a modem.

@{b}Q. MaxRexx seems to run slow, why?@{ub}

A. This is because of the amount of processing MaxRexx has to do, not only
does it have to monitor the ARexx port, it must process the commands it
receives and communicate with Maxs BBS as well. Not only that, you have
to include the parsing time for RX to parse your script. MaxRexx should
be at least acceptable on an 030@25Mhz.

@{b}Q. Why does MaxRexx catch some errors in the Arexx script but not others?@{ub}

A. MaxRexx only has limited error checking, it can't check for errors in your
script that are not MaxRexx commands, this is the job of RX. MaxRexx can
warn you if it receives a command that it doesn't understand.

@{b}Q. MaxRexx crashes on me, why?@{ub}

A. Firstly, make sure you meet the requirements. Secondly, make sure you are running
the correct version. MaxRexx.020 is an optimised version for 020 processors and above
only. If you ARE running this version, and HAVE an 020 or above, then try running the
68000 version. If it still crashes, E-mail me a bug report.



@{b}
@{u}Tips@{uu}

1. A common problem, especially with programmers new to AREXX is getting
quotation marks in the wrong position, for example:@{ub}

$GOTO 10,5
Incorrect!

$GOTO '10,5'
Correct!

If we had two variables called X and Y which we wanted to pass to the $GOTO
command:

$GOTO X,Y
Incorrect!

$GOTO 'X,Y'
Incorrect!

$GOTO X','Y
Correct!

Ok, so how does this work? Well with any command that is sent through an Arexx
port, anything contained within ' ' means send exactly what you see. Anything
contained outside those is deemed to be a variable, and ARexx tries to
substitute that variables value instead. If this seems a little confusing, look
at the script Everything.rexx and work you way through it.


@{b}2. You can quit MaxRexx at any time, on any node, even it it's running a script
by using quit.rexx and from the CLI entering:@{ub}

RX quit.rexx line

- Where line repesents the actual line number of the MaxRexx that you want to
quit. 0 for local, 2 for line 2 etc.


@endnode






